        "content": "<p>Hello.<br>\nI asked in <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/github.20permission/near/499272823\">this zulip</a> permission to create a branch to add hyperdoctrines to Mathlib.<br>\nIn my message I reference a <a href=\"https://www.math.mcgill.ca/seely/ZML/ZML.PDF\">paper from Robert Seely</a> in which this notion is defined.<br>\nI have been answered that this concept might not be fit for insertion into Mathlib as it was touching non-classical logics.<br>\nHyperdoctrines are a way to formalize the semantics of first order logics, in the same way as Heyting algebras allow us to formalize propositional logics (including both classical and non-classical logics).<br>\nSimilarly, hyperdoctrines can be used to formalize both classical and non-classical first order logics, even when using a classical metatheory (as that provided by Mathlib).<br>\nAn interesting instance of the structure of hyperdoctrines arise from (a fragment of) the internal logic of Grothendieck toposes and one of my coworker is currently working out this instance.<br>\nFor all these reasons, we think that Mathlib could benefit from being added a notion of hyperdoctrines and first order hyperdoctrines (i.e. hyperdoctrines over Heyting algebras)<br>\nWhat do you think ?</p>",
        "id": 499494874,
        "sender_full_name": "Samy Avrillon",
        "timestamp": 1739458726
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I personally think that hyperdoctrines are in scope for mathlib. A classical library can still have theory about non-classical logics (-; And of course hyperdoctrines have a bunch of applications besides non-classical logics.</p>",
        "id": 499497466,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1739459335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll make a note that <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"112680\">@Johan Commelin</span> volunteers to review :)</p>",
